element.name: Exchange Point
element.documentation: A domain for establishing energy exchange between two Metering Grid Areas. Additional information: This is a type of Metering Point

element.name: Metering Point
element.documentation: An entity where energy products are measured or computed.

element.name: Flexibility D/R Product Operator
element.documentation: The 'D/R product operator' role is responsible to adjust electricity consumption or generation in response to system operator (TSO/DSO) and/or market signals.

element.name: Party Connected to the Grid
element.documentation:
A party that contracts for the right to consume or produce electricity at an Accounting Point, Connection Point and/or Point of Common Coupling.
alias: Aangeslotene

element.name: System Operator
element.documentation:
A party responsible for operating, ensuring the maintenance of and, if necessary, developing the system in a given area and, where applicable, its interconnections with other systems, and for ensuring the long-term ability of the system to meet reasonable demands for the distribution or transmission of energy.
Based on: Consolidated text: Directive (EU) 2019/944 (https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX%3A02019L0944-20220623)

element.name: Grid Access Provider
element.documentation: A party responsible for providing access to the grid through an Accounting Point and its use for energy consumption or production to the Party Connected to the Grid.

element.name: Accounting Point
element.documentation: A domain under balance responsibility where Energy Supplier change can take place and for which commercial business processes are defined.

element.name: Flexibility Service Provider
element.documentation:
A party that offers flexibility services based on acquired (aggregated) Resources.
Flexibility is used to meet the needs of System Operators or other energy market participants on different energy-, power- or capacity marketplaces. Flexibility Services may be balancing services, non-frequency ancillary services, congestion management services etc.
There can only be one Flexibility Service Provider (FSP) responsible for a Resource for a delivery period, but a Flexibility Service Provider may have many Resources at the same time.

element.name: Registered Resource
element.documentation:
A Resource delivers the capability to modify generation injection and/or consumption patterns in the energy system (like electricity or gas). It is a market representation of an asset, or a group of assets having this capability. A Resource represents for example grid assets, energy generating units, energy consuming units, energy storing units or a virtual power plant.

element.documentation: The different types of services that may be used by an organization, i.e., electric, gas, water

element.documentation:

Service Delivery Point configuration. SDPLocationConfig contains additional position point information in addition to mail address and contact information.

element.name: Service Delivery Point
element.documentation:
The physical or virtual location where the flexibility service is delivered (e.g. load reduction, generation injection).
Defines the operational delivery of the D/R product and may be aggregated or virtual.
May coincide with the accounting point, but can differ (e.g. inside a facility behind one meter, or aggregated and located somewhere in the grid)

element.name: Predictive Operation Planning (POP)
element.documentation:
The Predictive Operation Planning (POP) business function is involved in forecasting future operation situations with an acceptable level of reliability, the inclusion of what-if scenarios and risk assessment.
This includes adequate management that requires system operators and planners to take into account scheduled and reasonably expected unscheduled availability of equipment, while maintaining a constant balance between supply and demand.

element.name: Grid Topology and Connection Point Service
Switching Schedule Creation
element.documentation: Generating schedules for switching actions, including both remote-controlled and manually operated switches.

element.name: Crew Dispatch Planning
element.documentation: Planning and scheduling the dispatch of field crews for manual switch operations.

element.name: Switch Action Scheduling (SAS)
element.documentation:
The Switch Action Scheduling (SAS) business function is involved in the scheduling and all relevant coordination of switching action.
This includes the creation of switching schedules for remote control switches and for switches that requires the dispatch of crews. Different schedules alternatives can be created to be used in an assessment process.

element.name: Remedial Action Schedules
element.documentation:
The Remedial Action Schedules business object includes the description of preventive, curative and restorative remedial action and the schedule for the activation. System Integrity Protection Scheme (SIPS) would be part of the network model. However, activation and arming of existing SIPS would be part of remedial action schedules. In addition, it includes proposals for new SIPS as part of system development planning.
== Remedial Action Plan --> Remedial Action -->
Remedial Action Schedules (as defined in Operating Constrains)

element.name: Availability Schedule
element.documentation:
The Availability Schedule business object includes the time intervals during which a grid element is available or not.
For grid elements normally in service, the focus is on the period that the grid element will not be available to provide functionality to the network. For grid elements normally out of service, or that have been forced out of service through network constrains or faults, the focus would be on when it is back in service.
For grid elements in test mode, the focus is on the period during which it will be in service.

element.name: Adequate Assessment
element.documentation: The Adequate Assessment business object includes the assessment of expected consumption compared to available production and transmission capacity.

element.name: Operational Settings Schedule
Contingency List
element.documentation: The Contingency List business object includes the list of grid elements that should be included as part of contingency assessment

element.name: Energy Forecast
element.documentation:
The Energy Forecast business object includes forecast for consumption (conformed or non-conformed including demand response), production (primarily intermittent or price inelastic production), direct current and area inter-exchange. This also includes energy forecasts for intermittent or price inelastic production that is part of Distributed Energy Resources (DER).
== business object (generic) energy prediction -> energy forecast / energy estimation

element.name: Planned Customer Outage
element.documentation: The Planned Customer Outage business object describe a planned event and the related information in regard to not being able to deliver the customer the committed service according to the customer agreement. The customer may or may not be compensated. The customer is informed in advance of planned outages. The reason for the outages is normally related to new construction, maintenance or repair either directly on the customer installation or to a nearby part of the Customer Installation connected to the grid.

element.name: Swtiching Schedule
element.documentation: The Switching Schedule business object includes the schedule and sequence for the opening and closing of switches.

element.name: Coordinate Contingency Analysis Service
element.documentation: Performs N-1 and other contingency simulations in collaboration with system operators or regional security coordinators to assess grid resilience against sudden equipment failures.

element.name: Predictive Security Assessment (PSA)
element.documentation:
The Predictive Security Assessment (PSA) business function involves coordination with dependent system operators or regional security coordinators for assessing different predicted grid situation abilities to withstand sudden, unexpected disturbances, such as short circuits or unanticipated loss of system equipment owing to natural causes.
The extended assessment would also involve withstanding disturbances caused by manmade physical or cyber-attacks.
Typically, the assessment is done using an N-1 criterion, where loss of any one given equipment will still leave the grid operating inside the defined operational limits. However, other methods, such as probabilistic assessment, can also be used.

element.name: Outage Notification Service
element.documentation:
Purpose: Notify relevant parties about planned or forced outages.
Covers: Market communication, customer notification, internal alerts.

element.name: Grid Topology Coordination Service
element.documentation:
The 'Grid Topology Coordination Service' provides an energized topology, including the functional electrotechnical components, their mutual relationships and measurements, the postion of the different active demand/response products based on a specific use case.
Purpose: Coordinate the availability status of grid elements with internal and external stakeholders.
Covers: In/out-of-service requests, inter-entity coordination, work scheduling.

element.name: Availability Scheduling Service
element.documentation: Purpose: Coordinate the availability status of grid elements with internal and external stakeholders. Covers: In/out-of-service requests, inter-entity coordination, work scheduling.

element.name: Availability Request Management (ARM)
Predictive Operational Capacity (POC)
element.documentation:
The Predictive Operational Capacity (POC) business function involves the calculation of cross-zonal capacity and congestion management in regard to where potential congestion needs to be resolved though changes in the energy schedules.
In areas where a balancing market is in place, this will be solved as part of operation. However, as part of predictive operation planning, this business function needs to use predictive merit order of the energy connection to simulate the price inelastic.

element.name: Remedial Action Impact Evaluation
element.documentation:
Purpose: Analyze the impact of activated remedial actions on grid safety and capacity.
Covers: Scenario-based analysis for planning and real-time support.

element.name: Predictive Operational Safety Validation
element.documentation: Purpose: Ensure the predicted grid state remains within safe operational boundaries. Covers: Validation against operational limits, state estimation, and gap filling.

element.name: Predictive Capacity Adequacy Service
element.documentation:
Purpose: Provide forward-looking assessments of system adequacy under forecasted load and generation scenarios.
Supports: predictive operational planning and system reliability.

element.name: Predictive Adequate Assessment (PAA)
element.documentation:
The Predictive Adequate Assessment (PAA) business function is involved in evaluations of the forecasts and schedules for consumption, production capacity, direct current capacity and area inter-exchange to assess the capacity adequacy.
This includes the evaluation of sufficient resources to provide customers with a continuous supply of electricity of the proper voltage and frequency through all time periods.
Resources refer to a combination of electricity generating and transmission facilities that produce and deliver electricity, and demand-response programmes that reduce customer demand for electricity.

element.name: Predictive Grid Risk Assessment Service
element.documentation:
Purpose: Deliver a quantified assessment of electrotechnical risks based on forecasted states, operational limits, and contingencies.
Covers: Core service of evaluating grid conditions under risk scenarios.

element.name: Enery Demand & Load Prediction Service
element.documentation:
The 'Enery Demand & Load Prediction Service' predicts the injection and with-drawn of energy in an area or point in the grid based on multi conditions, like wheater, etc. A prediction is based on meter readings or predefined profiles.
Alias: Energy Inject & With-drawn Prediction Service

element.name: Interconnection Flow Forecasting
element.documentation:
Purpose: Forecast cross-border or inter-area power exchange. Covers: Area inter-exchange predictions critical for grid balancing.
also known as: TenneT Demand Prediction Service

element.name: Energy Forecasting (EF)
element.documentation: The Energy Forecasting business (EF) function involves the forecasting of one or more of the items consumption (load), production (primarily intermittent or price inelastic production), direct current and area inter-exchange. This also includes energy forecasts for intermittent or price inelastic production that is part of the Distributed Energy Resources (DER).

element.name: Predictive Operational Condition Planning (OCP)
element.documentation:
The Predictive Operational Condition Planning (OCP) business function involved the scheduling of:
• device status (switch status, tap position, shunt bank position); • control settings (voltage regulation, flow regulation); • monitoring (operational limit determination, critical grid elements, topology limitation (power transfer corridors) and stability limits.
This also includes planning and optimisation for Distributed Energy Resources (DER) in regard to power characteristics settings.
Key functions: - Provisioning of Limits: Supplies relevant parties (e.g., system operators, control centers, or energy management systems) with predefined or dynamically calculated equipment operating limits.
- Validation and Versioning: Ensures that provided limits are current, technically validated, and tracked over time (e.g., through version control and timestamps).
- Integration with Operational Processes: Supports grid or process operation by feeding limits into security assessment tools, contingency analysis, and real-time monitoring systems.
- Compliance Support: Enables adherence to regulatory, safety, or manufacturer requirements for equipment operation.
- Change Notification: Triggers alerts or updates when operating limits change due to maintenance, upgrades, or operational conditions.

element.name: Cable Fault Detection and Location Service
Temporary Override Comitted
element.documentation: The operator (capacity) commited a temporary changes to limit with period or interval.

element.name: System Operational Limit Updated
element.documentation: Event indicating recalculated or changed limit is available, this event can be related to an equipment or equipment container, or to an area with changes in the offered D/R products.

element.name: Temporary Override Requested
element.documentation: The operator (capacity) requests temporary changes to limit with period or interval

element.name: System Operational Limit Retired
element.documentation: Equipment removed, limit no longer relevant

element.name: Predictive Energy Scheduling (PES)
element.documentation:
The Predictive Energy Scheduling (PES) business function involves the establishment of predictive energy schedule for consumption, production, direct current and area inter- exchange.
This also includes predictive energy scheduling for intermittent or price inelastic production that is part of Distributed Energy Resources (DER)

element.name: Network Operation (NO)
element.documentation:
The Network Operation (NO) package in the CIM IRM defines the business functions and business objects involved in monitoring and operating the power grid as a whole system or the entities responsible for part of the whole system.
The Network Operation business function includes real-time operation, which handles the execution of planned actions in addition to ensuring that the power grid is operating in a secure and balanced state. It also includes obligated operation planning that handles the " look-ahead" function to ensure that the " near future" operation based on committed schedules is an operation in a secure and balanced state.

element.name: Real-Time Operation (RTO)
element.documentation:
The Real-Time Operation (RTO) business function includes the execution of the planned action in regard to changing the network operational state. In addition, it monitors the current state of the network to ensure that the power grid is operating in a secure and balanced state. Predefined and activated remedial action will be executed when the pre-condition is met.
That a system is secure and balanced state means that there is balance between supply and demand and that the system can handle pre-defined unanticipated loss of system equipment without violating operational requirements in regard to voltage, frequency, and operational stability limits.

element.name: Safety Procedure Enforcement
element.documentation: Implementation of critical safety protocols during switching. Risk mitigation for personnel and equipment.

element.name: Remote Switching Execution
element.documentation: Operation of grid devices via SCADA (Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition). Remote modification of system controls.

element.name: Grid Impact Analysis
element.documentation: Evaluation of the impact of switching on grid stability. Use of analytical tools to assess the security of the resulting grid state.

element.name: Switching Order Supervision
element.documentation: Oversight and coordination of switching operations. Ensuring proper execution of scheduled switching tasks.

element.name: State Evaluation (SE)
Volt-VAr Optimization
element.documentation: Optimizes voltage profiles and reactive power flows.

element.name: Grid State Control Execution
element.documentation: - Issues instructions to field controls to change grid state. - Supports both closed-loop and man-in-the-loop operations.

element.name: Control Logic Processing
element.documentation: - Processes raw measurements or evaluated state. - Develops proposed changes using control algorithms (e.g., Optimal Power Flow).

element.name: Fault Location, Isolation, and Service Restoration (FLISR)
MeterReading Source Registration and Configuration Process
element.documentation:
What this service provides: This service manages the registration and configuration of meter reading sources. It enables the setup, validation, and maintenance of source information, including device identifiers, communication parameters, and data acquisition settings.
Goal: To ensure that all meter reading sources are correctly registered, configured, and maintained, enabling accurate, consistent, and reliable data collection across the energy system.

element.name: Real-Time Measurement Intake Service
element.documentation:
"Real-Time Measurement Intake" Why this fits: - "Real-Time" captures the temporal aspect. - "Measurement" is more inclusive than "SCADA" or "phasor data" and applies across all data types mentioned. - "Intake" implies collection, validation, and passive acquisition, aligning with the idea that the source is unaware and the data is raw, not coordinated.
Ensures all incoming data is accurately timestamped and synchronized to support real-time analytics and decision-making.

element.name: Real-Time System State Estimation Support
element.documentation: Provides foundational data for determining the current state of the controlled system.

element.name: MeterReading Validation Service
element.documentation:
What this service provides: This service ensures that the collected meter observations are accurate, consistent, and reliable by validating, processing, and aligning measurement data from different sources.
Goal: To deliver trustworthy and high-quality metering data that supports operational decision-making, billing, and regulatory compliance.

element.name: Real-Time Data Acquisition (RTDA)
Forced Unavailability
element.documentation: The Forced Unavailability business object includes the description of a piece of equipment's unavailability by the utility owing to operating constraints or in the course of restoring an unplanned outage in the same part of the network

element.name: Energy Scheduele
element.documentation: The Energy Schedule business object includes the schedule for consumption (conformed or non-conformed, including demand response), production (primarily intermittent or price inelastic production), direct current and area inter-exchange. This also includes the energy forecast for intermittent or price inelastic production that is part of Distributed Energy Resources (DER)

element.name: Real-Time Measurement
Post Event Assessment
element.documentation: The Post Event Assessment business object describes the results of post-event analysis.

element.name: Frequency Restoration Reserve
Network Operating Event
element.documentation: The Network Operation Event business object include: • event logs information; that capture outage and other relevant • records for equipment incorrect operation; to ascertain the cause of its • planned and unplanned maintenance data including root cause and repair/replacement details.

element.name: State Assessment
Energy Contract
element.documentation: The Energy Contract business object includes the conditions for demand response and provision of ancillary services or any other energy contract that is relevant for operational control

element.name: Switch Order
element.documentation: The Switch Order business object includes a sequence of switch open/close operations, tagging operations, device setting changes, other network operations and safety procedures to change the configuration of the network to achieve a particular business goal. The business goal could be to isolate part of the network in order to allow crews to work safely, to isolate a fault or to optimize the network based on various criteria, for example. Switch Orders can also be used to coordinate live line work safely. The switch order records the result of the switching operations, including who performed the switching and when the switching operation was performed. Both the control room operator and field crews, if any, are recorded with the switch order. This information: • includes a view of all incoming work on the systems. Work details are recorded for each set of switching actions (examination of manual and remote-controlled operations, work characteristics, and crews involved in the work); • provides a view of all switching states in addition to the open or closed state of the switch or device. This includes operational tags used to prevent device operations and safety documents to transfer authority between the control room and field crews.

element.name: Frequency Response Activation
element.documentation: The Frequency Response Activation business object includes the description of activation of frequency reserve in regard to correct an over or under frequency event.

element.name: Control Execution
element.documentation: The Control Execution business object includes the control commands to remotely operated devices and monitors the responses back to ensure correct operation or create an alarm if the operation fails.

element.name: Switch Execution
element.documentation: The Switch Execution business object includes the description of the act of manually opening or closing a switch by a field crew, rather than via remote control

element.name: Post Event Analysis (PEA)
element.documentation: The Post Event Analysis (PEA) business function includes the evaluation historical incident or situation of interest to identify the root cause and taking steps to prevent a similar occurrence in the future. Training, remedial action plans or other prevention schemes could be created based on a post event analysis.

element.name: Post Event Reporting
element.documentation: Documentation and communication of findings and recommendations.

element.name: Incident Evaluation Services
element.documentation: Analysis of historical incidents or situations. Identification of root causes.

element.name: Training Services
element.documentation: Development and delivery of training programs based on incident analysis.

element.name: Preventive Strategy Development
element.documentation: Creation of strategies to prevent recurrence of similar incidents. Implementation of lessons learned.

element.name: Obligated Operation Planning (OOP)
element.documentation: The Obligated Operation Planning (OOP) business function involves the "look-ahead" function to ensure that the "near future" operation, based on committed schedules is operation in a secure and balanced state. That a system is in a secure and balanced state means that there is balance between supply and demand and that the system can handle pre- defined unanticipated loss of system equipment without violating operational requirements in regard to voltage, frequency, and operational stability limits. In the case of a violation, predefined remedial action is applied

element.name: Obligated Reliability Assessment (ORA)
element.documentation: The Obligated Reliability Assessment business function is the " look-ahead" analysis based on current network operation state and the committed schedules to assess if future network operation is in a secure and balanced state. That a system is in a secure and balanced state means that there is balance between supply and demand and that the system can handle pre-defined unanticipated loss of system equipment without violating operational requirements in regard to voltage, frequency, operational stability limits. In the case of a violation, predefined remedial action is applied. It is particularly relevant to perform this prior to taking equipment out of service.

element.name: Reliability Assessment Service
element.documentation:
Key Functions:
- Analyze current network conditions and committed schedules. - Assess whether future operations will maintain: -- Balance between supply and demand. -- System resilience to predefined unanticipated equipment losses. -- Compliance with operational requirements (voltage, frequency, stability). - Trigger predefined remedial actions in case of predicted violations. - Support decision-making before taking equipment out of service.

element.name: Energy Schedule Execution
element.documentation: Implementing the established energy schedules in real-time operations.

element.name: Energy Scheduling
Real-Time Schedule Monitoring & Adjustment
element.documentation: Continuously tracking adherence to schedules and making adjustments as needed.

element.name: Energy Balancing (EB)
element.documentation: The Energy Balancing (EB) business function involves the evaluation of the balancing instruction that is prepared as part of planning activity that ensures that energy supply meets energy demand.

element.name: Support for Grid Stability
element.documentation: Contribute to the reliability of the energy grid by validating balancing strategies.

element.name: Balancing Instruction Analysis
element.documentation: Review and assess instructions for balancing energy supply and demand.

element.name: Demand-Supply Alignment
element.documentation: Ensure that planned energy supply meets forecasted demand.

element.name: System Development Planning (SDP)
element.documentation: The System Development Planning (SDP) business function involves network development and long-term planning. The business function support cooperation and coordination to develop a secure, environmentally sustainable and economic network system aimed at an adequate grid for the purpose of a well-functioning network operation and market operation. This is done through good planning with focus on future infrastructure characteristics, efficient asset management, critical infrastructure protection and system operability perspective

element.name: Transient Stability Analysis (TSA)
element.documentation: The Transient Stability Analysis business function involves the establishment of the necessary equipment features to meet the transient stability operational requirement for supporting different fault conditions

element.name: Network Situation
element.documentation: The Network Situation business object includes the description of the operational condition, operational settings and estimated injections on the network. Different situations are defined that should be used in training, simulation/analysis and validation

element.name: Network Capacity Assessment
element.documentation: The Network Capacity Assessment business object includes assessment of the maximum secure capacity of an intact network grid

element.name: Capacity Calculation Analysis (CCA)
element.documentation: The Capacity Calculation Analysis business function involves the establishment of the maximum secure capacity of intact network grid

element.name: Voltage Stability Analysis (VSA)
element.documentation: The Voltage Stability Analysis business function involves the establishment of the necessary equipment features to meet the voltage stability operational requirement for supporting different fault conditions

element.name: Short-Circuit Analysis (SCA)
element.documentation: The Short-Circuit Analysis business function involves the establishment of the necessary equipment features to meet the steady-state operational requirement for supporting different fault conditions

element.name: Reliability Calculation Analysis (RCA)
element.documentation: The Reliability Calculation Analysis business function involves the establishment of the necessary equipment, system protective configuration to meet the required reliability and operational goal of new construction.

element.name: Market Settlements (MS)
element.documentation: The Market Settlement (MS) business function includes the settlement of market contracts for energy and capacity: including energy, ancillary services, and the deployment of reserves for real-time balancing of supply and demand. It includes the settlement of bilateral contracts (non-standard contracts) and the settlement for the use of the transmission and distribution network.

element.name: Market Credit Clearing
element.documentation: The Market Credit Clearing (MC) business function involves the calculation of the total loans by borrowers and total supply of loans from lenders. The totally exposure can include trade that is not settled, trade settled but not invoiced, and trade invoiced but not paid. In some markets, the clearing is done by separate financial institution that net the exposure in all different markets.

element.name: Settlement Statement Assessment
element.documentation: The Settlement Statement Assessment business object describes the result of comparing the billing components/Settlement Statement from another party with the internal calculation based on observation and trading records.

element.name: Settlement Quality Trade
element.documentation:
The Settlement Quality Trade business object describes the data that meets the quality required by the settlement function defined in the Market Rules.
Settlement data may include the measurement of energy produced and consume, instructions issued by market operators to resources, and the response of market resources to these instructions.

element.name: Financially and Ancillary Settlement
element.documentation:
Purpose: Financially settle capacity commitments and ancillary service deliveries.
Covers: Non-energy product settlement components.

element.name: Capacity & Market Product Settlement
element.documentation:
Purpose: Settle transactions for standard market products (demand / reponse) including energy, capacity, and ancillary services.
Covers: Core financial reconciliation based on those transactions.

element.name: Market Trade Settlement (MTS)
element.documentation: The Market Trade Settlement (MTS) business function includes the settlement of standard market products that are traded on a market place. The products include energy, capacity, ancillary service and deployment of reserves for real-time balancing.

element.name: Trade Data Management (TDM)
element.documentation: The Trade Data Management (TDM) business function involves validation and aggregation of cleared trade data and creates settlement quality data defined by the market rules.

element.name: Charge Allocation Service
element.documentation:
Purpose: Calculate and allocate payment and charge shares to organizational partners.
Covers: Internal or contractual distribution of financial responsibilities.

element.name: Settlement Activation and Compliance Verification Service
Settlement Verification Service
element.documentation:
Purpose: Verify market settlement statements, payments, and charges.
Covers: Core "shadow settlement" activity, ensuring correctness of official settlements.

element.name: Dispute Support Service
element.documentation: Purpose: Provide verified settlement data to support dispute resolution processes. Covers: Input for handling discrepancies and resolving conflicts.

element.name: Market Settlement Verification (MSV)
element.documentation: The Market Settlement Verification (MSV) business function includes the verification of the market settlement statements payment and charges. It is sometimes referred to as "Shadow Settlement". This could provide the input to dispute resolution. The business function might also include the calculation of shares of the payment and charges to the organizational partners.

element.name: Grid Settlement (GS)
element.documentation: The Grid Settlement (GS) business function includes the settlement for the use of the transmission and distribution network

element.name: Network Model Management (NMM)
element.documentation:
The Network Model Management (NMM) package in the CIM IRM defines the business functions and business objects for establishing and maintaining the functional description of the network grid that is provided by the currently installed asset (as-built model), the planned installed asset (future model) or the potential installation (what-if/hypothetical model).
The focus is to provide a mathematical model of the network grid that can be used in different analysis of the grid, including, but not limited to, steady-state power flow, state estimation, contingency analysis as part of security assessment and stability analysis.

element.name: Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition Modelling (SCDAM)
element.documentation: The Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition Modelling (SCDAM) business function includes the modelling of alarm setting and monitoring, acquisition configuration, measurement and signalling structure and quality constrains.

element.name: Measurement Structure Modelling
element.documentation: Defines how measurements are structured, categorized, and interpreted.

element.name: Alarm Setting and Monitoring
element.documentation: Provides capabilities to define, configure, and monitor alarm thresholds.

element.name: Meter Acquisition Configuration
element.documentation: Manages the setup of meter acquisition parameters and source integration.

element.name: Meter Acquisition Parameters
element.documentation: Contains settings for data acquisition such as sampling rate, source ID, etc.

element.name: Alarm Configuration
element.documentation: Defines alarm thresholds, types, priorities, and associated actions.

element.name: Measurement Definition
element.documentation: Describes the structure, units, and types of measurements collected.

element.name: Quality Constraints
element.documentation: Specifies rules and thresholds for data accuracy, completeness, and timeliness.

element.name: Equipment Operating Limit Provisioning Service
element.documentation: A business service that provides validated and up-to-date information on the operational security limits of specific pieces of equipment within an energy system. These limits may include thermal, voltage, current, stability, or manufacturer-specified constraints that define the safe and reliable operating boundaries of the equipment.

element.name: Functional Topology Modelling Service
element.documentation:
Purpose: Support functional (logical) representation of network elements distinct from physical assets.
Covers: Substation, transmission, distribution, market, and role/actor modeling.

element.name: Power System Model Management
element.documentation:
Purpose: Provide access to and governance over current, past, and future power system models.
Covers: Master repository function, model lifecycle management.

element.name: Network Model Provisioning
element.documentation:
Purpose: Deliver consistent and versioned network models for analysis and planning.
Covers: On-demand access for simulations, planning, and operational tools.

element.name: Network Modelling (NM)
element.documentation:
The Network Modelling (NM) business function provides the means to maintain a network model as a master repository for the power system resources that are part of the model responsibility area. The repository should provide means for accessing network models for the past situation, current asbuilt and future situations. The network models represent the functional description of the power system needed for supporting different analyses. The functional model may differ from the functional representation given by the asset that is providing the functionality.
Relevant modelling fragments are: • Substation modelling • Transmission network modelling • Distribution network modelling • Production and consumption modelling • Market modelling • Electrical diagram modelling • Transient/dynamic modelling • Short-circuit modelling • Protection modelling • System Integrity Protection Scheme (SIPS) • Role and actor modelling • Pattern and hypothesis situation modelling • Training simulation modelling

element.name: Scenario Planning and Forecasting
element.documentation: Support future state modelling and hypothesis testing.

element.name: Network Model Repository Management
element.documentation: - Maintain a master repository of network models. - Support versioning for past, current, and future network states.

element.name: New Equipment Commissioned
element.documentation: Triggers creation of initial limit data on a specific Equipment or Equipment Container

element.name: Energy Connection Management (ECM)
element.documentation: The Energy Connection Management (ECM) business function involves the coordination of the relevant connection data and the documentation of the conditional approval of connecting power system elements to the network grid. This includes, but is not limited to, power-generating facilities, transmission system, high-voltage direct current cables, distribution system and demand facilitates.

element.name: Network Connection
element.documentation:
The Network Connection business object describes the conditional requirement for connecting equipment to the network grid.

element.name: Network Model
element.documentation: The Network Model business object includes the functional description of the network grid that used in one or more network analysis.

element.name: Engineering Design Management (EDM)
element.documentation: The Engineering Design Management (EDM) package in the CIM IRM defines the business functions and business objects involved in creating and maintaining detailed design (e.g. blueprints) of all the structures that constitute the relevant grid elements. These include substation engineering, transmission line engineering, distribution engineering, generation engineering, and so on.

element.name: Design Performance Simulation
element.documentation:
Simulating asset structure performance across different design stages: - As-planned - As-designed - As-built - As-operated
Integration with Operational and Planning Functions - Real-time simulation for Network Operation (NO) - Post-event simulation for System Development Planning (SDP) or other planning functions

element.name: Design Model Analysis (DMA)
element.documentation: The Design Model Analysis (DMA) business function involves the analysis to simulate the performance of the asset structure based on the detail design. The detail design could represent the structure and/or building in different stages, as-planned, as-designed, as-built or as-operated. The simulation of measure-based performance is done as part of Network Operation (NO) for real-time and System Development Planning (SDP) or other functional area after the fact simulation. Relevant power electronic analysis are: • small signal stability analysis; • dynamic simulation; • geomagnetic induced currents (GIC); • short-circuit calculation; • line properties calculation; • electromagnetic transients (EMT); • protection simulation; • cost calculation; • reliability.

element.name: Dynamic Simulation
element.documentation: Time-domain simulation of system behavior under dynamic conditions

element.name: Short-Circuit Calculation
element.documentation: Determining fault currents for protection and equipment rating

element.name: Line Properties Calculation
element.documentation: Analyzing electrical characteristics of transmission lines

element.name: Customer Management (CM)
element.documentation: The Customer Management (CM) package in the CIM IRM defines the business functions and business objects involved in the management of customer data and records, customer trouble calls, customer installation, customer agreements and settlement (creating the billing components that are aggregated as part of the billing process) and the development of new products.

element.name: Customer Programme Management (CPM)
element.documentation: The Customer Programme Management (CPM) business function involves the creation and maintenance of programs made available to customers such as various rate options or programs which will affect their usage/billing (e.g. demand response (DR))

element.name: Trouble Ticket
element.documentation: The Trouble Ticket business object describes the event and/or symptoms that may or may not affect the grid that is reported by a customer or third-party observer. The trouble ticket might be linked to an Incident, Unplanned Customer Outage or in some cases a Planned Customer Outage.

element.name: Network Extention Agreement
element.documentation: The Network Extension Agreement (or Network Extension Contract) business object is a specialisation of Customer Agreement where the commitment is in relation to extending an existing customer installation or the creation of a new customer installation

element.name: Customer
element.documentation: The Customer business object describes an individual person or business that has or has had an agreement with the utility in regard to provide goods or services.

element.name: Connection Feasibility
element.documentation: The Connection Feasibility business object described the result of a feasibility study for connection.

element.name: Customer Inquiry
element.documentation: The Customer Inquiry business object describes the inquiries from a given customer

element.name: Energy Agreement
element.documentation: The Energy Agreement (or Energy Contract) business object is a specialisation of Customer Agreement where the commitment is in relation to the delivery of energy to or from a given customer installation and customer. In some cases, this could also describe agreement in regard to active power that is delivered or consumed as well.

element.name: Customer Agreement
element.documentation: The Customer Agreement (or Customer Contract) business object describes the commitment between the service provider and a customer. The agreement describes the aspects of the service in regard to quality, availability and responsibilities.

element.name: Customer Installation
element.documentation: The Customer Installation business object describes the content of the installation on the customer premises in regard to installation, premise, point of delivery and device (e.g. a meter for meter reading) and their location (directly or relative to the connection to the grid)

element.name: Grid Connection Agreement
element.documentation: The Grid Agreement (or Grid Contract) business object is a specialisation of Customer Agreement where the commitment is in relation to the connection into the grid, distribution or transmission.

element.name: Billing Component
element.documentation: The Billing Component (or Settlement Statement, Customer Settlement Statement or Customer Billing Statement) business object describes the line items that constitute the charges and payment created as part of settling the contract signed with the customer. This provides some of the input to invoicing were pay and receivable and payment agreement is not included

element.name: Customer Energy Programme
element.documentation: The Customer Energy Programme business object describes the product that a customer can be entered into agreement with. It normally describes a way for a utility to control the customer installation as a reserve for balancing the grid in regard to demand (or in some cases production surplus). The customer is compensated for providing the flexibility and when the flexibility is activated. This could be a demand response product or other power effect control program

element.name: Customer Account Management (ACT)
element.documentation: The Customer Account Management (ACT) business function includes the creation, ongoing management (including responding to customer inquiries relative to their account), account billing, and account closing.

element.name: Contract Management (CM)
element.documentation: The Contract Management (CM) (or Contract Administration) business function involves the management of contracts/agreements with customer in regard to services to the customer installation, maintenance and creation of new customer installation.

element.name: Account Settlement (AC)
element.documentation: The Account Settlement (AC) (or Billing Management or Customer Settlement Management) business function involves the settlement calculation based on the customer agreement and the Settlement Quality observation (typically through a meter reading). This produces the items, statements or billing components that are used in the billing process for invoicing the customer.

element.name: Trouble Call Management (TCM)
element.documentation: The Trouble Call Management (TCM) business function manages the receipt of information from and communications to customers or other observation related to service to one of more customers. This involves the matching up of previous reported trouble ticket, know incident (in the related area) or unplanned (some cases planned) outages.

element.name: Customer Installation Management (CIM)
element.documentation: The Customer Installation Management (CIM) business function is managing the information related to the customer installation and connection to the grid. This includes line extension, fuse and capacity description, inspection and survival, meter installation and interconnection of additional devices (e.g. solar panels through an inverter) to the grid. This also includes the work definition, work task breakdown and request for a schedule of the work

element.name: Emergency Simulation (ES)
element.documentation: The Emergency Simulation (ES) business function involved operational training and operational planning with the use of network and situation simulation to prepare for emergency situations.

element.name: Alarm Training (AT)
element.documentation: The Alarm Training business function involves training in interpreting alarms and how to change the network operation so that the alarm situation is resolved.

element.name: Real-Time Operational Simulation Training (ROST)
element.documentation: The Real-Time Operational Simulation Training business function involves the training of operators in real-time operating environment such as control centres to operate a plant, facility or grid.

element.name: Compliance Test Plan
element.documentation:
The Compliance Test Plan business object includes legal (e.g. ownership), commercial, (e.g. supplier), financial (e.g. different type of cost), technical and managerial information for substation and network, energy resource (including distributed energy resource (DER)), and non-electrical asset that are included and used in a defence and restoration plan.
Identification of the network function and the physical assets are central items that allow for the retrieval of additional information associated with the asset and its network function.

element.name: Restoration Plan
element.documentation: The Restoration Plan business object includes the all technical and organisational measures necessary for the restoration of the system back to normal state.

element.name: Settlement Quality Observation Management (SQO)
element.documentation: The Settlement Quality Observation Management (SQO) business function includes processes that provide settlement quality data for the billing functions. These processes typically include measurement of energy, correction of errors and resolution of disputes.

element.name: Settlement Quality Assessment
element.documentation: The Settlement Quality Assessment business object describes the compliance with the observation supervision rules to see if the data is fit for purpose

element.name: Market Operation (MO)
element.documentation: The Market Operation (MO) business function involves the provision of a market-based allocation of energy, capacity and ancillary services based on bid-based market clearing. Market Operations produce schedules and balancing dispatch instructions that are feasible considering market and grid constraints.

element.name: Market Ancillary Clearing (MAC)
element.documentation: The Market Ancillary Clearing (MAC) business function includes provision of ancillary service based on clearing bids and offers for the volumes of ancillary service required to maintain the defined grid security and reliability

element.name: Market Scheduling (MS)
element.documentation: The Market Scheduling (MS) business function includes the creation of schedules based on a market result trade for energy, transmission, and ancillary services.

element.name: Trade-Based Scheduling Service
element.documentation: Purpose: Translate confirmed market trades into time-bound delivery schedules. Covers: Energy delivery, transmission allocation, and reserve provisioning

element.name: Market Schedule Generation
element.documentation:
Purpose: Create schedules based on market results for energy, transmission, and ancillary services.
Covers: Core transformation of trades into executable schedules.

element.name: Market Definition Management (MDM)
element.documentation:
The Market Definition Management (MDM) business function provides a definition of the market products, and the market timelines including gate closures.
For the European style market, this would include the definition of the energy congestion zone (e.g. Bidding Zone)..

element.name: Market Trading (MT)
element.documentation: The Market Trading (MT) business function involves the market participant's decision making, strategic and tactical, for creating bid and offers on market products.

element.name: Market Capacity Clearing (MCC)
element.documentation: The Market Capacity Clearing (MCC) business function includes provision of generation and transmission capacity based on bids and offers for the same capacity product. Options for allocation of transmission include explicit auctions, secondary trading of transmission rights, and implicit auctions. Long-term generation capacity can involve bilateral market mechanism or centrally run auction market

element.name: Operational Transmission Rights Management
element.documentation: Purpose: Enable trading, allocation, and administration of transmission rights. Covers: Explicit auctions and secondary market for transmission capacity.

element.name: Market Schedule
element.documentation: The Market Schedule (MS) business object includes the market resource allocation for a given product based on the Market Result. If multiple market resources can provide the product, the Market Merit Order is used to distinguish. For ancillary services, this could mean the providing reserve capacity

element.name: Meter Grid Area
element.documentation: The Meter Grid Area business object includes the description of an electrical area that has metered flow in and out of the area. Only a single entity is responsible for the metering of the area.

element.name: Trade Bit
element.documentation: The Trade Bid business object can be a bid or an offer on an identified resource and product with a price dependency. The bid/offer can be a curve of quantity of product offered or demanded at different price levels

element.name: Energy Congestion Zone
element.documentation: The Energy Congestion Zone business object includes the description of the board of the delivery of energy and capacity market products. Market participants' bids and offers can be cleared without congestion constraints. This is used in a zonal-based market, such as the European-style market

element.name: Market Result
element.documentation:
The Market Result business object describes the matched and cleared result of the trading. It includes the identification of resource, product and matched price.
== Settlement Dossier (Market Result)

element.name: Market Definition
element.documentation: The Market Definition business object describes the market definition, including products and pricing

element.name: Unified Pricing Location
element.documentation:
The Unified Pricing Location business object is a set of network nodes at which energy is injected or withdrawn from the network. The price of energy and ancillary services at each node within a pricing location is the same. The price of energy and ancillary services may be unique at different pricing locations. This is used in a nodal-based market, such as the North American-style market
== CIM: PricingNode

element.name: Compliance Verification
element.documentation: The Compliance Verification (CV) business function involves the verification and in some cases certification of a given party’s compliance with a set of market or supervision rules. An example rule is the testing and verification of communication links and compliance of metering data to quality standards.

element.name: System Operator
element.documentation: The System Operator business object is a specialization of Entity that describes an entity who is responsible for a stable and balanced power system operation for a given part of the power grid.

element.name: Market Rules
element.documentation: The Rules business object describes the rules that applies to all entities in a given market or inter-party operation. It describes the different roles that can be performed by the different parities to meet the covered compliance

element.name: Market Participant
element.documentation: The Market Participant business object is a specialization of Entity that describes an entity who participates in one or more markets through buying, selling, transmission, or distribution of energy, capacity or ancillary services into, out of, or through one or more areas of the power grid

element.name: Certification
element.documentation: The Certification business object describe a given entity's compliance with one or more market or supervision rules. An example is the certification of meeting the requirement for acting in the role of metering data provider. The

element.name: Fault Management (FM)
element.documentation: Fault Management gets notifications regarding faults in the electrical network and analyses those notifications in order to estimate the location of the fault. Fault Management tracks the fault through the stages of actual location, minimizing the area impacted by the fault, restoring service to all impacted parts of the network and coordinating permanent repairs. Fault Management ensures that fault durations and restoration times are correctly captured for regulatory reporting purposes.

element.name: Incident
element.documentation: The Incident business object describes an occurrence in the field that impacts or may impact the network grid. An incident may be reported as part of a trouble ticket. It may or may not be associated with an outage.

element.name: Fault Assessment
element.documentation: The Fault Assessment business object includes the result of analyses data received about the fault, in order to estimate the probable location of the fault.

element.name: Estimated Restoration Time
element.documentation: The Estimated Restoration Time business object is the time and date that service is expected to be restored for a particular fault. Estimated Restoration Time can be calculated automatically or can be based on estimates provided by field crews assigned to repairing the fault. The accuracy of Estimated Restoration Time can vary through the course of the lifecycle of each fault.

element.name: Field Fault Assessment
element.documentation: The Field Fault Assessment business object includes the information that is provided by a field crew sent to a predicted fault event. The field crew travels to the predicted location and determines if this is the actual location. If the predicted fault location is confirmed, then the assessment is complete. If the predicted fault location is incorrect, the field crew investigates other possible fault locations and reports the actual fault location, completing the assessment. The field crew may also subsequently report the cause of the fault, if the cause can be determined.

element.name: Unplanned Customer Outage
element.documentation: The Unplanned Customer Outage business object describes an unplanned event and the related failure of delivery the customer the committed service in accordance with the customer agreement. The customer may or may not be compensated.

element.name: Predictive Fault Event
element.documentation: The Predicted Fault Event business object includes the result of Fault Identification analysing input data, such as telemetered values, Trouble Tickets, End Device Events and field Fault Assessment data. The Predicted Fault Event is described by location, faulty equipment and phases.

element.name: Service Restoration
element.documentation: - Manages the process of restoring power to impacted areas. - Prioritizes restoration based on criticality and customer impact.

element.name: Restoration Operation Planning (ROP)
element.documentation: The Restoration Operation Planning (ROP) business function create a plan for handling unplanned or forced outage to recover to an acceptable operation state. It also includes a plan to restore the network to its pre-fault condition after repairs have been made.

element.name: Regulatory Reporting
element.documentation: - Captures and logs fault duration and restoration times. - Prepares data for compliance and regulatory reporting.

element.name: Restoration Coordination
element.documentation: - Coordinates field teams for permanent fault repair. - Ensures repair activities are scheduled and executed efficiently.

element.name: Fault Analysis and Localization
element.documentation: - Analyzes incoming fault data to estimate the fault location. - Uses algorithms or historical data to narrow down fault zones.

element.name: Fault Notification Reception
element.documentation: - Receives and logs fault alerts from the electrical network. - Interfaces with monitoring systems and sensors.

element.name: Fault Tracking and Monitoring
element.documentation: - Tracks the fault through its lifecycle. - Monitors changes in fault status and updates stakeholders.

element.name: Fault Identification (FI)
element.documentation: The Fault Identification (FI) business function uses a variety of inputs in order to identify where the real fault has occurred. It will also identify the cause of the fault, where known.

element.name: End Device Reading
element.documentation: The End Device Reading business object represents the data that have been acquired by the end device. A meter reading that provides the cumulative kWh value recorded by a meter device from a previous reading, or a meter reading on an hourly resolution for a period are examples of end device readings. A fault reading from a remote fault recorder is also an example of an end device reading

element.name: End Device Event
element.documentation: The End Device Event business object is information provided by the end device based on the end device configuration and represents the occurrence of an event that has been under monitoring. Meter tampering and grounding error are examples of end device events

element.name: Meter Data
element.documentation: Meter data that are integrated over a period of time before being presented for billing or other purposes.

element.name: Settlement Quality Observation
element.documentation: The Settlement Quality Observation business object describes the data that meets the quality required by the settlement "function defined in the Market Rules. For example, a meter" reading can include the cumulative kWh value that needs to have the previous meter reading subtracted to calculate the consumption from previous billing components. The consumption value could be considered as settlement ready data that meets the requirement defined in the market rules.

element.name: Telemeter Fault Signature
element.documentation: The Telemetered Fault Signature business object includes one or more remotely monitored measurements from sensors that are used to identify the location of a Predicted Fault Event. The Telemetered Fault Signature could be waveform data from a fault recording device, fault passage and direction from fault passage indicator devices, fault distance from a relay, fault current from a relay, the open/close status of a switch or an analogue voltage/flow measurement

element.name: End Device Data Acquisition (EDA)
Observation Data Management (ODM)
element.documentation: The Observation Data Management (ODM) business function validates readings and other observation measurement against agreed quality rules. Observation that does not meet the requirement can be user edited or estimated bases on rules. The appropriate supervision rules for validating, editing and estimating (VEE) are normally defined by the relevant supervising regulatory agency.

element.name: Meter Data Management (MDM)
element.documentation: The Meter Data Management (MDM) business function collects, validates, stores and distributes readings and event- related data from meters and other end devices to other enterprise functions and systems. The meter data management function supports diverse end-use applications including but not limited to billing, load management, load forecasting, demand response, outage management, asset management and distribution network planning and maintenance. The function may perform validating, editing, and estimating (VEE) according to rules established by the appropriate supervising regulatory agency

element.name: Environment Forecast
Environment Forecasting (EF)
element.documentation: The Environment Forecasting business function are estimating the intensity, nature, and timing of the external forces that may affect the construction, operation and maintenance of power utility asses or function in regard to performance, firms, disrupt or force changes to existing plans and strategies. For power utilities, this is relevant for weather warnings and real-time data for load forecasting.

element.name: Environmental Conditions Changed
element.documentation: Triggers recalculation of situational limits

element.name: Asset Management (AM)
element.documentation:
The Asset Management (AM) business function coordinates activities of an organisation to realise value from assets. Assets are in general considered to be items, things or entities that have potential or actual value to an organisation. This business function is focused on physical assets in the power system.
Asset Management involves the balancing of cost, opportunities and risks against the desired performance of assets, to achieve the organisational objectives (see ISO 55000).

element.name: Technical Attribute Management Service
element.documentation: Store and maintain technical specifications and operational characteristics for each asset type.

element.name: Financial Asset Tracking Service
element.documentation: Record and manage financial aspects of assets, including cost types, valuations, and depreciation.

element.name: Asset Registration Service
element.documentation:
Register new assets (substation, network, energy resource, non-electrical grid, non-grid) into the asset register.
Capture legal, commercial, financial, technical, and managerial attributes for each asset.

element.name: Asset Record Management (ARM)
element.documentation:
The Asset Record Management (ARM) business function involves the registration and maintenance of the legal (e.g. ownership), commercial (e.g. supplier), financial (e.g. different type of cost), technical and managerial information for:
• Substation and Network Assets
The electrical substation and network assets that a utility owns, or for which it has responsibility, maintained in an accurate asset register developed around an asset hierarchy that supports advanced asset management functions.
• Energy Resource Asset
Record of the Energy Resource, including Distributed Energy Resource (DER), that can be aggregated to provide power necessary to meet demand. These resources refer to distributed generation, storage, load management, combined heat and power and other sources involved in electricity supply, both in stand-alone and interconnection applications.
• Non-Electrical Grid Asset
The non-electrical assets (e.g. poles, cross-arms, etc.) that a utility owns, or for which it has responsibility, maintained in an accurate asset register that supports advanced asset management functions.
• Non-Grid Asset
The non-grid assets (e.g. tools, vehicle, etc.) that a utility owns or responsibility for that is not related directly to the network grid.

element.name: Asset Limit Updated
element.documentation: Event indicating recalculated or changed limit is available, this event can be related to an asset value or policy..

element.name: Asset Maintenance Plan
element.documentation: The Asset Maintenance Plan business object specifies the activities, resources and timescales required for an individual asset, or a grouping of assets, to achieve the organization’s asset management objectives and prevent expected impact of asset failure.

element.name: Asset Work Record
element.documentation: The Asset Analytics Result business object includes various analytic scores for the asset, asset type or group of asset (e.g. breakers from a given manufacture) that describe the criticality to the organisation, performance targets or standards, non-conformance criteria, operating cost, replacement value, downtime impact and health assessment

element.name: Asset Functional Characteristics
element.documentation: The Asset Functional Characteristics business object describes the combination and interdependencies of asset data (technical information), engineering data, design parameters, environment conditions (both static and dynamic), asset condition data and asset maintenance strategy to form the safe operational space and operational constraints. For example, inherent/permanent thermal rating of assets deployed in the network including changes in electrical asset performance limits based on temperature, wind speed and solar radiation, which set the frame for a variety of actual operational limits on network elements.

element.name: Asset Test Result
element.documentation: The Asset Analytics Result business object includes various analytic scores for the asset, asset type or group of asset (e.g. breakers from a given manufacture) that describe the criticality to the organisation, performance targets or standards, non-conformance criteria, operating cost, replacement value, downtime impact and health assessment

element.name: Asset Catalogue
element.documentation: The Asset Catalogue (AC) business object includes the information of asset grouping with relevant specification to provide information on a given set of generic asset material to be used in strategic planning, design/acquisition, operations, maintenance and renewal/disposal.

element.name: Asset Maintenance Strategy
element.documentation: The Asset Maintenance Plan business object specifies the activities, resources and timescales required for an individual asset, or a grouping of assets, to achieve the organization’s asset management objectives and prevent expected impact of asset failure.

element.name: Asset
element.documentation:
The Asset business object includes legal (e.g. ownership), commercial (e.g. supplier), financial (e.g. different type of cost), technical and managerial information for substation and network, energy resource (including distributed energy resource (DER), and non-electrical assets.
Identification numbers (specification number, product number, serial number) are central items that allow for collection of additional information associated with the asset.

element.name: Asset Condition
element.documentation: The Asset Condition business object describes a given asset or asset type key performance indicators for given operational condition, performance targets or standard, operational safety and reliability assessment.

element.name: Asset Failure
element.documentation: The Asset Failure business object describes the failure history or statistics associated with a given asset, asset type or asset group (e.g. breakers from a given manufacturer). This includes burnout and accidents.

element.name: Asset Analytics Result
element.documentation: The Asset Analytics Result business object includes various analytic scores for the asset, asset type or group of asset (e.g. breakers from a given manufacture) that describe the criticality to the organisation, performance targets or standards, non-conformance criteria, operating cost, replacement value, downtime impact and health assessment

element.name: Asset Compliance Reporting
element.documentation: The Asset Compliance Reporting business object describes compliance to organisation realisation of asset management in regard to value, efficiency and effectiveness, integrity, execution and leadership against regulatory, standard and business requirements. This could include reporting on compliance to maintenance strategy, maintenance execution, deliverables, and continual improvement. Reporting can be done on individual asset, asset type and asset group in regard to operational, reliability and security standards and regulations. It can also include their impact on the environment in regard to government regulation.

element.name: Asset Financial Performance
element.documentation:
The Asset business object includes legal (e.g. ownership), commercial (e.g. supplier), financial (e.g. different type of cost), technical and managerial information for substation and network, energy resource (including distributed energy resource (DER), and non-electrical assets.
Identification numbers (specification number, product number, serial number) are central items that allow for collection of additional information associated with the asset.

element.name: Asset Conditional Information
element.documentation: An Asset Conditional Information describes the rule and value, under which conditions to operate a asset.

element.name: Asset Monitoring (AM)
element.documentation: The Asset Monitoring (AM) business function involves inspection, testing, measurement, and monitoring of the assets in order to understand, assess and manage their condition and performance

element.name: Asset Decision Support (ADS)
element.documentation: Asset decision support involves strategy definition and prioritisation, maintenance strategy planning, risk management, programme management and decision-making. The central aspect of asset decision support is analytics. It drives the condition, configuration, performance, operating costs, and flexibility of the asset base, with the aim of maximising value.

element.name: Geographical Inventory (GINV)
element.documentation: Management of geospatial data, typically by utilizing computer graphics technology to enter, store, and update graphic and non-graphic information. Geographic depictions and related non-graphic data elements for each entity are typically stored in some form of a data store. The graphic representations are referenced using a coordinate system that relates to locations on the surface of the earth. Information in the data store can be queried and displayed based upon either the graphic or non-graphic attributes of the entities.

element.name: Network Operation Monitoring (NMON)
element.documentation: Provides the means for supervising main substation topology (breaker and switch state) and control equipment status. It also provides the utilities for handling network connectivity and loading conditions. It also makes it possible to locate customer telephone complaints and supervise the location of field crews.

element.name: Asset Monitoring and Measurement (AMM)
element.documentation: Asset monitoring and measurement involves inspection, testing, measurement, and monitoring of the assets in order to understand, assess and manage their condition and performance.

element.name: Substation and Network Inventory (EINV)
element.documentation: The electrical substation and network assets that a utility owns, or for which has legal responsibility, and will maintain an accurate asset register developed around an asset hierarchy that supports advanced asset management functions.

element.name: Maintenance and Inspection (MAI)
element.documentation: Work involving inspection, cleaning, adjustment, or other service of equipment to enable it to perform better or to extend its service life. Examples of maintenance work are routine oil changes and painting. Examples of inspection work are pole inspections, vault inspections, and substation inspections.

element.name: Work Scheduling and Dispatching (SCHD)
element.documentation: Work scheduling and dispatching makes it possible, for a defined scope of work, to assign the required resources and keep track of work progress.
